chapter 10 demo clustering

Agglomerative hierarchical clustering

  • Agglomerative clustering (bottom-up)

  • Starts with as each sample in its own cluster

  • Joins the two most similar clusters

  • Then, joins next two most similar clusters

-Continues until all samples are in one cluster

Given the sample correlation matrix

##                 JPMorgan Citybank WellsFargo RoyalDutchShell ExxonMobil
## JPMorgan            1.00     0.63       0.51            0.12       0.16
## Citybank            0.63     1.00       0.57            0.32       0.21
## WellsFargo          0.51     0.57       1.00            0.18       0.15
## RoyalDutchShell     0.12     0.32       0.18            1.00       0.68
## ExxonMobil          0.16     0.21       0.15            0.68       1.00

-When the sample correlations are used as similarity measures,

  • Variables with large negative correlation are regarded as very dissimilar. Variables with large positive correlation are regarded as very similar.

-Base on the fact that “hclust” function only reads a dissimilarity structure, hence, a transformation required to cluster the the stocks using these hierarchical procedures is 1-correlation as follow.

# construct the similarity measurement given the correlation matrix: 1-cor
stock_dis = as.dist(1-stock_col )
stock_dis

Single linkage

  • The inputs to a single linkage algorithm can be distances or similarities between pairs of objects. Groups are formed from the individual entities by merging nearest neighbors.

-We find the smallest distance in \(D=\{d_{ik} \}\) and merge the corresponding objects say \(U\) and \(V\), to get the cluster \((UV)\).

  • The distance between \((UV)\) and any other cluster \(W\) are computed by \(d_{(UV)W} = \text{min} \{d_{UW},d_{VW} \}\)

where the quantities \(d_{UW}\) and \(d_{VW}\) are the distances between the nearest neighbors of clusters \(U\) and \(W\) and clusters \(V\) and \(W\), respectively.

\[ \begin{array}{lc} \mbox{} & \begin{array}{cc} 1 && 2 && 3 && 4 && 5\end{array} \\ \begin{array}{c} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \\ 4 \\ 5 \end{array} & \left[\begin{array}{cc} 1 \\ 0.63 & 1 \\ 0.51 & 0.57 & 1 \\ 0.12 & 0.32 & 0.18 & 1 \\ 0.16 & 0.21 & 0.15 & \underline{0.68} & 1 \end{array}\right] \end{array} \Rightarrow \begin{array}{lc} \mbox{} & \begin{array}{cc} 45 && 1 && 2 && 3 \end{array} \\ \begin{array}{c} 45 \\ 1 \\ 2 \\ 3\end{array} & \left[\begin{array}{cc} 1 \\ 0.16 & 1 \\ 0.32 & \underline{0.63} & 1 \\ 0.18 & 0.51 & 0.57 & 1 \end{array}\right] \end{array} \Rightarrow \begin{array}{lc} \mbox{} & \begin{array}{cc} 45 && 12 && 3 \end{array} \\ \begin{array}{c} 45 \\ 12 \\ 3 \end{array} & \left[\begin{array}{cc} 1 \\ 0.32 & 1 \\ 0.18 & \underline{0.57} & 1 \end{array}\right] \end{array} \Rightarrow \begin{array}{lc} \mbox{} & \begin{array}{cc} 45 && 123 \end{array} \\ \begin{array}{c} 45 \\ 123 \end{array} & \left[\begin{array}{cc} 1 \\ \underline{0.32} & 1 \end{array}\right] \end{array} \]

# single linkage 
single_linkage_stcok = hclust(stock_dis, method = "single")
plot(single_linkage_stcok,  sub="",xlab="Stock", main="Cluster Dendrogram using Single Linkage")

-In the cluster dendrogram using single linkage, undoubtedly, RoyalDutchShell connects with ExxonMobil at first, followed by JPMorgan and Citybank with the second highest correlation 0.63. And the last, WellsFargo links to Citybank with the correlation 0.51. After that, the remaining two clusters form the dendrogram.

Complete linkage

  • Complete linkage clustering proceeds in much the same manner as single linkage clustering. In complete linkage at each stage, the distance between clusters is determined by the distance between the two elements one from each cluster, that are most distance.

-First we find the minimum entery in \(D=\{d_{ik} \}\) and merging the corresponding objects, say \(U\) and \(V\), to get the cluster \((UV)\).

-The distance between \((UV)\) and any other cluster \(W\) are computed by \(d_{(UV)W} = \text{max} \{d_{UW},d_{VW} \}\)

# complete linkage hierarchical procedure
complete_linkage_stock = hclust(stock_dis, method = "complete")
plot(complete_linkage_stock,  sub="",xlab="Stock", main="Cluster Dendrogram using Complete Linkage")

# avaerage linkage hierarchical procedure
average_linkage_stock = hclust(stock_dis, method = "average")
plot(complete_linkage_stock,  sub="",xlab="Stock", main="Cluster Dendrogram using Complete Linkage")

-Calculate the Euclidean distances between pairs of countries

dis = dist(data, method = 'euclidean',diag = T); #dis

Cluster the countries using the sinlge linkage, complete linkage and Ward’s hierarchical procedures and then compare the results.

1. Single linkage

# single linkage
single_linkage_track = hclust(dis, method = "single")
plot(single_linkage_track,  sub="",xlab="Country", main="Cluster Dendrogram using Single Linkage", cex=0.5, ylab="Distance")
segments(4,12.5,7,12.5, col="green")

conslusion In the cluster dendrogram using single linkage procedure, it is suggested that there are two clusters based on the cut at the distance 12.5 (green line).

1: COK, PNG and SAM

2: the rest of the countries

2. Complete linkage

# complete linkage 
complete_linkage_track = hclust(dis,  method = "complete")
plot(complete_linkage_track,  sub="",xlab="Country", main="Cluster Dendrogram using Complete Linkage", cex=0.5, ylab="Distance")
abline(h=35, col="red")

conslusion In the cluster dendrogram using complete linkage procedure, three possible clusters are identified if we cut the dendrogram at distance 35 (red line).

Cluster 1: COK, PNG and SAM

Cluster 2 and 3: can be observed from the above dendrogram.

3. Ward’s method

-Ward considered hierarchical clustering procedures based on minimizing the “loss of information” from joining two groups.

# ward's hierarchical clustering method
ward_linkage = hclust(dis, method = "ward.D")
plot(ward_linkage,  sub="",xlab="Country", main="Cluster Dendrogram using Ward's method", cex=0.5, ylab="Distance")
segments(5,80,33,80, col="green")
segments(43,200,70,200, col="green")

conslusion In the above cluster dendrogram using Ward’s method, three clusters have been chose based on the cuts.

4.Average linkage

# avg linkage hierarchical procedure
avg_linkage = hclust(dis, method = "average")
plot(avg_linkage,  sub="",xlab="Country", main="Cluster Dendrogram using Average Linkage", cex=0.5, ylab="Distance")
segments(1,18,25,18, col="red")
segments(50,35,55,35, col="red")

In the cluster dendrogram using average linkage, it coincides with the expectation that there are three clusters.

-Even though these dendrograms yield different clustering results, it may be stated that PNG, COK and SAM are “similar” by all four dendrograms. Also, dendrograms using complete linkage procedure and Ward’s method are quite similar to each other.

Note :The clusters are more apparent in the complete linkage dendrogram and, depending on the distance level, might have as few as 3 or 4 clusters or as many as 6 or 7 clusters.

Silhouette plots for K=3 and K=4

# silhouette plots construction
# k=3
sil_3 = silhouette(km3$cluster, dis)
plot(sil_3, main = "Silhouette plot for 3-means",  col = c("red", "green", "blue"))

# k=4
sil_4 = silhouette(km4$cluster, dis)
plot(sil_4, main = "Silhouette plot for 4-means",  col = c("red", "green", "blue", "purple"))

-By comparison of the average silhouette widths, it seems that K=3 is a desire number of clusters.

conclusion

Overall, it has a proclivity for, say, three clusters in terms of the distances between pairs of countries, as evidenced by not only the dendrograms generated using the entire linkage approach, Ward’s method, and average linkage, but also the silhouette plot with K=3 results.

Because the merge requirement of a single linkage technique is purely local, near overlap is more likely to cause confusion. Consider the case where a chain of points can be stretched across large distances without regarding to the overall shape of the emerging cluster (chaining effect).

####   silhouette value for Kmeans cluster =2

Silkm2=silhouette(km2$cluster,dist(data))
